rest_of_day_open: I have an imminent writing deadline coming up, so that’s what’s been weighing on me the most. Tomorrow night I might watch a friend’s online movie stream if I can spare the time? critical_positive: I felt like we both went in with few expectations and remained inquisitive throughout the conversation, with a mutual curiosity about some esoteric subjects. There was also a similarity in political ideology that probably helped. Not to mention waiting for each other to finish, and apologizing for any inadvertent interruptions
critical_negative: I didn’t really feel like there were any major issues? One general problem with the whole blind-conversation format is that you go in knowing absolutely nothing about the other person, whereas at a party even a total stranger might have some common interest you can guess at, a mutual friend.

rest_of_day_open: I see it being productive and forward thinking but with a lot of uncertainty and background anxiety about the future. I have important decisions to make with my life, choosing a path that will lead to meaningful work, and hopefully leading me somewhere in life that I would want to be. Whatever happens, I want to stay engaged with my life.
critical_positive: What worked well was when we let each other talk about our own interests and look for common ground that could be a source of connection. It worked best when we could each express what we feel most intense and passionate about, and my conversation partner and I found common ground in both of our outlooks on the world.
critical_negative: What didn't work so well was when it felt we got a bit caught up on certain minutiae of famous figures that we were talking about... the conversation dragged a bit when I felt like I couldn't connect with my partner on modernist literature at the same level as him. We were a little cagey at first on sharing political opinions or worldviews, but opened up our opinions near the end of the call.
